We now show that the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) Bellman optimality operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\) optimizes a lower bound on the percentile criterion. Given a policy \(\pi\), a state \(s\in\mathcal{S}\), and transition probabilities \(\bm{P}\), let

\[(\mathcal{T}_{\tilde{\bm{P}}}^{\pi}\bm{v})_{s}=\sum_{a\in\mathcal{A}}\pi(s,a) \bm{p}_{s,a}^{\mathsf{T}}(\bm{r}_{s,a}+\gamma\bm{v})\enspace,\]

represent the Bellman evaluation operator for transition probabilities \(\bm{P}\). Furthermore, let

\[(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\bm{v})_{s}=\sum_{a\in\mathcal{A}} \pi(s,a)\,\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}\left[\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}^{\mathsf{T}}(\bm{r}_{ s,a}+\gamma\bm{v})\right]\enspace,\]

represent the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) Bellman evaluation operator for random transition probabilities \(\tilde{\bm{P}}\). We use \(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\) to denote the fixed point of \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\). Furthermore, we use \(\tilde{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\) to represent the random fixed point of \(\mathcal{T}_{\tilde{\bm{P}}}^{\pi}\), which is computed using a random realization of the transition probabilities \(\tilde{\bm{P}}\) sampled from the posterior distribution conditioned on observed transitions \(\mathcal{D}\).

**Proposition 3.2** (Lower Bound Percentile Criterion).: _For any \(\delta\in(0,\nicefrac{{1}}{{2}})\), if we set the confidence level \(\alpha\) in the operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}^{\delta}\) to \(\nicefrac{{\delta}}{{S}}\), then for every policy \(\pi\in\Pi:\Pr_{\tilde{\bm{P}}}\left[\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\preceq\tilde{\bm{v}}^{ \pi}|\mathcal{D}\right]\geq 1-\delta\)._

Proposition 3.2 shows that for any policy \(\pi\) and state \(s\), the \(\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}\) value at state \(s\), \(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}(s)\) lower bounds the true value \(\tilde{\bm{v}}^{\pi}(s)\) with high confidence. Comparing Proposition 3.2 with the definition of the percentile-criterion in (1), we see that the percentile-criterion requires confidence guarantees only on the returns computed from the initial states, whereas the equation in Proposition 3.2 provides confidence guarantees on the value of every state. Therefore, for any policy \(\pi\), the value \(\bm{p}_{0}^{\mathsf{T}}\tilde{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\) is a lower bound on the percentile-criterion objective \(\mathrm{VaR}_{\delta}[\rho(\pi,\tilde{\bm{P}})]\). Since \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\) finds a policy \(\pi\) that maximizes the value \(\bm{p}_{0}^{\mathsf{T}}\tilde{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\), it follows [37] that \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\) optimizes a lower bound on the percentile criterion in (1).

**Proposition 3.3**.: _Suppose that \(\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}\) for any state \(s\) and action \(a\), is a multivariate sub-Gaussian with mean \(\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}\) and covariance factor \(\bm{\Sigma}_{s,a}\), i.e., \(\mathbb{E}\left[\exp\left(\lambda(\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}-\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a})^ {\mathsf{T}}\bm{w})\right]\leq\exp\left(\lambda^{2}\bm{w}^{\mathsf{T}}\bm{ \Sigma}_{s,a}\bm{w}/2\right),\forall\lambda\in\mathbb{R},\forall\bm{w}\in \mathbb{R}^{S}\). Then, for any state \(s\in\mathcal{S}\), \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\) satisfies_

\[(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\bm{v})_{s}\geq\max_{a\in\mathcal{A}} \left(\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}^{\mathsf{T}}\bm{w}_{s,a}-\sqrt{2\ln(\nicefrac{{1}} {{\alpha}})}\sqrt{\bm{w}_{s,a}\bm{\Sigma}_{s,a}\bm{w}_{s,a}}\right)\enspace.\]

_As a special case, when \(\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}\) is normally distributed \(\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}\sim\mathcal{N}(\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a},\bm{\Sigma}_{s,a})\), then \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\) for any state \(s\in\mathcal{S}\) can be expressed as_

\[(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\bm{v})_{s}=\max_{a\in\mathcal{A}}\left( \tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}^{\mathsf{T}}\bm{w}_{s,a}-\Phi^{-1}(1-\alpha)\sqrt{\bm{w}_{ s,a}\bm{\Sigma}_{s,a}\bm{w}_{s,a}}\right)\enspace.\]

Proposition 3.3 shows that by assuming that the transition probabilities are sub-Gaussian, we can easily compute a lower bound of the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) Bellman update \((\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\bm{v})\) for a given value function using only the mean and the covariance matrix of \(\tilde{\bm{P}}\). In the special case where \(\tilde{\bm{P}}\) is normally distributed, we can compute the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) Bellman optimality operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}(\bm{v})\) exactly.

### Performance Guarantees

We now derive finite-sample and asymptotic bounds on the loss of the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) framework.

**Theorem 3.4** (Performance).: _Let \(\hat{\bm{v}}\) be the fixed point of the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) Bellman optimality operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\) and \(\pi^{*}\) be the optimal policy in (1). Let \(\rho^{*}=\mathrm{VaR}_{\delta}\left[\rho(\pi^{*},\tilde{\bm{P}})\right]\) denote the optimal percentile returns and \(\hat{\rho}=\bm{p}_{0}^{\mathsf{T}}\hat{\bm{v}}\) denote the lower bound on the percentile returns computed using the Bellman operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\) with \(\alpha=\nicefrac{{\delta}}{{S}}\). Then for each \(\delta\in(0,\nicefrac{{1}}{{2}})\):_

\[\rho^{*}-\hat{\rho}\leq\frac{1}{1-\gamma}\max_{s\in\mathcal{S}}\max_{a\in \mathcal{A}}\left(\mathrm{VaR}_{1-\frac{1-\delta}{3}}\left[\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}^ {\mathsf{T}}\bm{w}_{s,a}\right]-\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}\left[\tilde{\bm{p}}_{s,a}^ {\mathsf{T}}\bm{w}_{s,a}\right]\right)\enspace.\] (6)

Theorem 3.4 bounds the finite sample performance loss of the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) framework. The loss varies proportionally to the maximum difference between the \(\nicefrac{{\delta}}{{S}}\) and \(1-(\nicefrac{{1-\delta}}{{S}})\) percentile of the one-step Bellman update for the optimal robust value function \(\hat{\bm{v}}\). Furthermore, the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) framework performs better when the uncertainty in the transition probabilities is small.

**Theorem 3.5** (Asymptotic Performance).: _Suppose that the normality assumptions on the posterior distribution \(\tilde{\bm{P}}\) in Section 2 are satisfied. For any \(\delta\in(0,\nicefrac{{1}}{{2}})\), set \(\alpha=\nicefrac{{\delta}}{{S}}\) in \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{VaR}_{\alpha}}\). For any state \(s\) and action \(a\), let \(I(\bm{p}^{*}_{s,a})\) be the Fisher information matrix corresponding to the true transition probabilities \(\bm{p}^{*}_{s,a}\). Furthermore, let \(\sigma^{2}_{\mathrm{max}}=\max_{s\in\mathcal{S},a\in\mathcal{A}}\tilde{\bm{w}} ^{\mathsf{T}}_{s,a}I(\bm{p}^{*}_{s,a})^{-1}\tilde{\bm{w}}_{s,a}\) be the maximum over state-action pairs of the asymptotic variance of the returns estimate \(\tilde{\bm{p}}^{\mathsf{T}}_{s,a}\tilde{\bm{w}}_{s,a}\). Then the asymptotic performance of the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) framework \(\hat{\rho}\) w.r.t. the optimal percentile returns \(\rho^{*}\) satisfies_

\[\lim_{N\to\infty}\sqrt{N}(\rho^{*}-\hat{\rho})\leq\frac{1}{1-\gamma}\left(2 \Phi^{-1}(1-\nicefrac{{\delta}}{{S}})\sigma_{\mathrm{max}}\right)\leq\frac{ 1}{1-\gamma}\sqrt{8\ln(\nicefrac{{\delta}}{{S}})}\sigma_{\mathrm{max}}\enspace.\]

Theorem 3.5 shows that the asymptotic loss in performance of the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) framework convergence to 0, i.e., \(\lim_{N\to\infty}(\rho^{*}-\hat{\rho})=0\).

