## Appendix A Additional theoretical results

**Definition A.1** (Translation Subvariance).: The operator \(\mathfrak{T}:\mathbb{R}^{S}\to\mathbb{R}^{S}\) satisfies the _translation subvariance_ property if for all vector \(\bm{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{S}\) and scalar \(c\), there exists \(\gamma\in[0,1)\) that satisfies

\[\mathfrak{T}(\bm{v}+c\bm{1})=(\mathfrak{T}\bm{v})+\gamma c\bm{1}\ \ \.\]

**Definition A.2** (Monotonicity).: The operator \(\mathfrak{T}:\mathbb{R}^{S}\to\mathbb{R}^{S}\) satisfies the _monotonicity_ property if for all \(\bm{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{S}\) and \(\bm{u}\in\mathbb{R}^{S}\) such that \(\bm{v}\preceq\bm{u}\), \(\mathfrak{T}\) satisfies

\[\mathfrak{T}\bm{v}\preceq\mathfrak{T}\bm{u}\ \ \.\]

**Lemma A.3** (Contraction Mapping [6]).: _The operator \(\mathfrak{T}:\mathbb{R}^{S}\to\mathbb{R}^{S}\) is a contraction mapping if it satisfies monotonicity and translation subvariance properties, i.e., there exists \(\gamma\in[0,1)\) such that for all \(\bm{u}\in\mathbb{R}^{S}\), \(\bm{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{S}\), \(\mathfrak{T}\) satisfies_

\[\|\mathfrak{T}\bm{u}-\mathfrak{T}\bm{v}\|_{\infty}\leq\gamma\|\bm{u}-\bm{v}\| _{\infty}\.\]

The proof of Lemma A.3 follows directly from Proposition 2.1.3 in [6]. We re-derive the proof for the sake of completeness.

Proof.: Denote

\[c=\max_{s\in S}|\bm{u}_{s}-\bm{v}_{s}|\.\]

Therefore for all \(s\in\mathcal{S}\),

\[\bm{u}_{s}-c\leq\bm{v}_{s}\leq\bm{u}_{s}+c\.\]

Applying \(\mathfrak{T}\) to these inequalities and using the _translation subvariance_ (Definition A.1) and _monotonicity_ (Definition A.2) properties, we obtain that for all \(s\in\mathcal{S}\),

\[(\mathfrak{T}\bm{u})_{s}-\gamma c\leq(\mathfrak{T}\bm{v})_{s}\leq(\mathfrak{ T}\bm{u})_{s}+\gamma c\.\]

It follows that for all \(s\in\mathcal{S}\),

\[|(\mathfrak{T}\bm{v})_{s}-(\mathfrak{T}\bm{u})_{s}|\leq\gamma c\,\]

and therefore \(\|\mathfrak{T}\bm{u}-\mathfrak{T}\bm{v}\|_{\infty}\leq\gamma c\), proving the stated result.

**Lemma A.4**.: _For any policy \(\pi\), let \(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\) and \(\bm{v}^{\pi}\) be the fixed point of the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) policy evaluation operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\) and Bellman policy evaluation operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\vec{P}}^{\pi}\). If the VaR Bellman policy evaluation operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\) dominates the Bellman policy evaluation operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\vec{P}}^{\pi}\) at \(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\), i.e., \(\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\preceq \mathcal{T}_{\vec{P}}^{\pi}\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\), then, the fixed point of the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) Bellman evaluation operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\) dominates the fixed point of the Bellman evaluation operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\), i.e., \(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\preceq\bm{v}^{\pi}\)._

We note that in contrast to the Bellman policy evaluation operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\vec{P}}^{\pi}\), the \(\mathrm{VaR}\) Bellman policy evaluation operator \(\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\) is a function of the random variable \(\hat{\bm{P}}\) and is not dependent on the transition probabilities \(\bm{P}\) assumed in this setting.

Using the assumption \(\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\preceq\mathcal{T}_ {\vec{P}}^{\pi}\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}\), and from \(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}=\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi}\hat{\bm{v}}^ {\pi}\) and \(\bm{v}^{\pi}=\mathcal{T}_{\vec{P}}^{\pi}\bm{v}^{\pi}\), we get by algebraic manipulations:

Proof.: \[\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}-\bm{v}^{\pi}=\mathcal{T}_{\nabla\mathrm{aR}_{\alpha}}^{\pi} \hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}-\mathcal{T}_{\vec{P}}^{\pi}\bm{v}^{\pi}\preceq\mathcal{T}_ {\vec{P}}^{\pi}\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}-\mathcal{T}_{\vec{P}}^{\pi}\bm{v}^{\pi} \preceq\gamma\bm{P}_{\pi}(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}-\bm{v}^{\pi})\ \.\]

Here \(\bm{P}_{\pi}\) is the transition probability function corresponding to policy \(\pi\). Subtracting \(\gamma\bm{P}_{\pi}(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}-\bm{v}^{\pi})\) from the above inequality gives,

\[(\bm{I}-\gamma\bm{P}_{\pi})(\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}-\bm{v}^{\pi})\preceq\bm{0}\ \.\]

where \(\bm{I}\) is the identity matrix. \((\bm{I}-\gamma\bm{P}_{\pi})^{-1}\) is monotone as can be seen from its Neumann series.

\[\hat{\bm{v}}^{\pi}-\bm{v}^{\pi}\preceq(\bm{I}-\gamma\bm{P}_{\pi})^{-1}\bm{0}= \bm{0}\ \.\]

which proves the result.

